- math that creates the inputted frequency

- want 30.5 mHz--> goes from 36 mHz to 53 mHz over 33 ms
- limited by I2C(bust bandwidth limit), even if parameters can be fast enough, cant tell the board fast enough
- limited by hardware
- RPLL's, PLL
- all clocks share the same PLL...may lead to fewer solutions that work
- signal to noise ratios, so that's why it's a higher 900 mHz
- markdown: can render in github(looks nice when you pull it up on the web browser, text readMe file, markdown, embed this image from my assets folder), embedded pictures
- study(better resolution from 30.5 vs 30.6)(limits, sig figs, blindly test min and max for this thing)

- GOAL = 30.5 mHz(divide the VCO by the crystal frequency)
- Output = 25 mHz * PLL multiplier/d/rdiv
- PLL multiplier = a + b/c
    - rdiv = 1, or needs to be a power 2
    - below 500 kHz then no
- we favor 900 mHz to make it deterministic(would expect the same outcome no matter what is done...)
    - 900/30.5 = ~28
    - 30.5 * 28 = 854 mHz(should be within 600-900) = VCO
    - d = remainder at this point = 28
    - 854/25 = 34.16 mHz
    - a = 34, b = 4, c = 28




